	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Intelligence v.s. Charisma:<BR>
<BR>
If you are in a well balanced experience gathering group, the pace of the fighting will be determined by the healer.  &quot;Pull until the Cleric screams&quot; basically sums it up.  For multiple pulls, they may consult the Enchanter, but basically as long as everyone is at full health, the puller continues to pull.  When the healer starts to get low on mana, the puller slows down.  If anyone else runs out of mana, it's their OWN FAULT.  All other casters (including the Enchanter) need to ration their mana.<BR>
<BR>
Your main job is to keep people from dying.  That means providing crowd control--with one caveat.  Don't get so caught up trying to mez the second mob that you catch aggro, making the cleric use needed mana to keep YOU alive.  Sometimes it is better to let the second mob beat on the well armored tank, than to risk having it beat on your poorly armored hide.<BR>
<BR>
That being said, the only excuse you have for running out of mana is a potentially disastrous overpull.  If you run out of mana, that means the healer is out of mana, and there's a good chance someone is going to die.<BR>
<BR>
Your second job is to improve the efficiency of the group.  That means Clarity (or Breeze) on yourself and your healer AT ALL TIMES.  And any other casters as appropriate.  Tashan on the mobs if there are nukers in the group.  Also, speed buffs on the meleers (including pets) and charisma buffs on yourself, if you have the mana.  After that, debuffs on the mobs if you have the mana and it is efficient.  If the average mob lasts less than a half minute, don't bother slowing it down.  DoT spells sometimes are worth it, sometimes not.  Damage shield on the tank if you are the only one that can cast it and if it makes sense.  Color Flux stunning can reduce damage for very little mana output if you can avoid possible problems.<BR>
<BR>
In case of mana glut, (if the puller is slow or if the mobs just don't spawn quickly enough) and you actually get to full mana, and everyone is buffed to the hilt, THEN you can start thinking about nuking.  Or using the different illusion spells.  You may want to rethink which buffs you are using.  Use Alacrity on the Rogue or Monk instead of Augmentation, for example.  It uses more mana, but allows him to hit more often.  Hopefully, he won't be needing the AC or Stamina components, anyway.<BR>
<BR>
The point of this analysis is this: You will probably be spending most of your time fluctuating between 60% and 90% mana.  Much lower than that and you start leaving out buffs or debuffs.  Much higher than that, and you start putting in extras.  Since mana regeneration is a function of your meditation skill and your clarity/bard song buffs, there will not be a significant advantage to having more intelligence.  The ONLY time having more intelligence will help is in the case of overpull.  In which case you will be frantically trying to mez all the extra mobs.  I know from casting mez on myself with different charisma gear that charisma DOES have a pretty good effect on resist rates.  Figure the cost of having one of your mez spells resisted.  Best case it's just the loss of mana, and it's just a re-mez of a current mezzy.  Worst case, you could catch aggro and waste precious time, mana, and health recasting between interrupts.  And it could snowball from there.  Cleric has to heal you, catches aggro and now is trying to cast between interrupts.  I've seen it happen.  An entire fight goes bad from just one resist.  Of course I've seen a fight go bad when I ran out of mana, too, but it's usually due to multiple mez resists.  How many of those could have been avoided had I opted for more charisma instead of intelligence?<BR>
<BR>
I pretty much always opt for charisma over intelligence.  I HATE having my mez spells resisted.  The respect that you get from your group after a well controlled overpull is very gratifying.  Even when you do get resisted, they're very helpful and understanding, but it isn't quite the same if the Shammy had to Root one or if the Cleric had to Stun one for you.<BR>
<BR>
Of course if you like to solo, you're much more likely to need lots of intelligence, and less likely to need charisma.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
